Q1)

Assume that you have a biased coin, and you want to simulate tossing an unfair coin experiment to see how law of large numbers works. In this experiment probability of turning up heads is 0.7.

a) Simulate the proportions of turning on heads by taking sample size n=1000. You are only allowed to use uniform random number generator.

b) Try to obtain plot below. (On the y-axis, the proportions of the heads should be, and on the x-axis, how many times did you continue this experiment namely, number of replicates.)

n = 10^3;
U = runif(n, min = 0, max = 1);
toss = U < 0.7;
a = numeric(n + 1);
avg = numeric(n);

for(i in 2 : n + 1){
  a[i] = a[i - 1] + toss[i - 1];
  avg[i - 1] = a[i]/(i - 1);
}


plot(1 : n, avg[1 : n], type = "l", lwd = 1.3, col = "blue", ylab = "ProportionofHeads",
     xlab = "CoinT ossNumber", cex.main = 1.25, cex.lab = 1.5, cex.axis = 1.75)

Q2)

Generate a sample from Gamma(2, 1) distribution conditional on its value being greater than 5, that is

\[ f(x) = \frac{xe^{-x}}{\int_5^{\infty}xe^{-x}dx} \] Using rejection sampling.

(Hint: Assume g(x) be the density function of exponential distribution.)

Since Gamma(2,1) random variable has expected value 2, we use an exponential distribution with mean 2 that is conditioned to be greater than 5.

\[ f(x) = \frac{xe^{-x}}{\int_5^{\infty}xe^{-x}dx} = \frac{xe^{-x}}{6e^{-5}}\ (5 \leq x) \]

\[ g(x) = \frac{\frac{1}{2}e^\frac{-x}{2}}{e^\frac{-5}{2}}\ (5 \leq x) \] \[ \frac{f(x)}{g(x)}= \frac{x}{3}e^{\frac{-(x-5)}{2}} \]

We obtain the maximum in x = 5 since \(\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\) is decreasing. Therefore,

\[ c= \frac{f(5)}{g(5)}=\frac{5}{3} \]

  • Generate a random variable Y distributed as G(Y)

  • Generate random variable U

  • If U < \(\frac{x}{5}e^{\frac{-(x-5)}{2}}\) accept set Y=X, otherwise go back to step 1.

set.seed(2022)  # for reproducibility
n = 10^4        # sample size
i <- 0  # number of iteration
k <- 0 # counter for accepted
y <- numeric(n) # random sample
c <- 5/3


while (k < n) {
  u = runif(1)
  i <- i+1
  x = 5 - 2*log(runif(1))
  if (u <= (x/5) * exp(-(x-5)/2 * c)) {
    k <- k + 1
    y[k] <- x
  }
}
i;k;length(y)
## [1] 23205
## [1] 10000
## [1] 10000
summary(y)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   5.000   5.249   5.597   5.846   6.182  11.566
hist(y, prob = TRUE, main ="f(x)=(a*exp(-a))/(6*exp(-5))")
a = seq(min(y), max(y), 0.01)
lines(a, (a*exp(-a))/(6*exp(-5)), col="red",lwd = 2.5)

Q3)

Let \(X \sim Cauchy(\mu,s)\) and let p be a real number. You want to approximate the probability \(P(X < p_1)+P(x > p_2)\), by taking \(\mu=-2\), \(s=4\) and \(p_1= 0.9\) and \(p_2=3\).

PDF of Cauchy Distribution;

\[ f(x)=\frac{1}{\pi s[1+ (\frac{x-\mu}{s})^2]},\ \text{where s>0 and x€}(-\infty,\infty) \]

CDF of Cauchy Distribution;

\[ \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \frac{1}{\pi s[1+ (\frac{x-\mu}{s})^2]},\ \text{where s>0 and x€}(-\infty,\infty) \]

Approximate this integral using classical Monte Carlo Integration and calculate variance of the estimator.

set.seed(361)

# Step 1: Define f(X)

f <- function(x) function(x, s, mu){ 1/pi*s*(1+((x-mu)/s)^2)}


# Step 2: Define g(X)

g1 <- function(x, p1){
  if (x < p1) return(1)
  else return(0)
}


g2 <- function(x, p2){
  if (x > p2) return(1)
  else return(0)
}

# Step 3: Generate x1,...,xn  iid random variables

n <-10^5
mu <- -2
s <- 4
p1 <- 0.9
p2 <- 3

x <- rcauchy(n = n, scale= s, location  = mu)


# Step 4: Compute the estimate
 
probability1 = mean(sapply(x ,g1, p1))
probability2 = mean(sapply(x ,g2, p2))

estimate_classical = probability1 + probability2


cat("Estimated P(x < 0.9) + P(x > 3) =", estimate_classical,"\n")
## Estimated P(x < 0.9) + P(x > 3) = 0.91396
cat("Real probability value is:",pcauchy(p1, location = mu, scale = s) + (1- pcauchy(p2, location = mu, scale = s)),"\n")
## Real probability value is: 0.9144551
var_prob1 <- (mean(sapply(x ,g1, p1)^2) - (mean(sapply(x ,g1, p1)))^2) # Var(x) = E(X^2) - E(x)^2
var_prob2 <- (mean(sapply(x ,g2, p2)^2) - (mean(sapply(x ,g2, p2)))^2) # Var(x) = E(X^2) - E(x)^2


var_cauchy <- var_prob1 + var_prob2 + 2*cov(sapply(x ,g1, p1), sapply(x ,g1, p1))

cat("Variance of classical monte carlo is:" , var_cauchy)
## Variance of classical monte carlo is: 0.8001827

Q4)

You have a random variable whose distribution is given below;

\[ f(x) = \frac{k}{\lambda}* (\frac{x}{\lambda}) ^{k-1}\ e^{(\frac{-x}{\lambda})^k}\ , x>0 \]

Besides, you want to find probability P(x < 0.9) from f(X). Take \(\lambda=4\) and k=1.

a) Approximate this integral using classical Monte Carlo Integration and calculate variance of the estimator. After that check your result with real probability value.

# Step 1: Define f(X)

set.seed(1234)

weibull_dist <- function(x){ (k/lambda)*((x/lambda)^(k-1))*exp((-x/lambda)^k)}


# Step 2: Generate iid Uniform rvs x ~ Uniform and y ~ b-Uniform

n <- 10^5
k <- 1
lambda <- 4
a<- 0 ; b<- 0.9


x = runif(n, a, b)

# Step 3: Compute  estimate; g(Xbar)


g.X <- sapply(x, weibull_dist)
g.Xbar <- mean(g.X)

estimate_classical <- g.Xbar*(b-a)

var_classical <- var(g.X)*(b-a)^2

cat("Estimate Monte Carlo Integration;", estimate_classical, "\n", "Real probability value",  
    dweibull(0.9, shape = k, scale = lambda),"\n" ,"Variance of this estimator:" ,var_classical)
## Estimate Monte Carlo Integration; 0.201462 
##  Real probability value 0.1996291 
##  Variance of this estimator: 0.0001712883

b) Approximate this integral using antithetic variable approach and calculate variance of the estimator.

# Step 1: Define f(X)

set.seed(1234)

weibull_dist <- function(x){ (k/lambda)*((x/lambda)^(k-1))*exp((-x/lambda)^k)}


# Step 2: Generate iid Uniform rvs x ~ Uniform and y ~ b-Uniform

n <- 10^5
k <- 1
lambda <- 4
a<- 0 ; b<- 0.9


u = runif(n/2, a, b)
x = u
y = b - u


# Step 3: Compute  estimate; g(Xbar)

weibull_dist_x = weibull_dist(x) 
weibull_dist_y = weibull_dist(y)

antithetic <- (weibull_dist_x + weibull_dist_y)/2 # used estimate for antithetic approach

# Estimate 

weibull_dist_ant_estimate = mean(antithetic)*(b-a) # estimate with antithetic approach

cat("Estimate with antithetic approcah;", weibull_dist_ant_estimate )
## Estimate with antithetic approcah; 0.2014832
var.ant.estimate <- (var(weibull_dist_x)+var(weibull_dist_y)+2*cov(weibull_dist_x,weibull_dist_y)) / 4


# or;

var.ant.estimate <- var(antithetic)


cat("Antithetic variance of theta hat is ", var.ant.estimate)
## Antithetic variance of theta hat is  1.776574e-07

c) Approximate this integral using control variates and calculate variance of the estimator.

#define parameters
n <- 10^5
k <- 1
lambda <- 4
a<- 0 ; b<- 0.9


x = runif(n, a, b)

#define f(X) and g(X)

g.cont <- function(x) (k/lambda)*((x/lambda)^(k-1))*exp((-x/lambda)^k)
f.cont <- function(x) x^(k-1) * exp(-x)


# est of c*

cor(g.cont(x),f.cont(x)) # correlation is high, we satisfy the correlation between f and g.
## [1] 0.9962752
c_star_weibull <- -cov(g.cont(x),f.cont(x)) / var(f.cont(x))
c_star_weibull
## [1] -0.08509618
estimate_cont_weibull = mean(g.cont(x) + c_star_weibull * (f.cont(x) - (1/(b-a))*integrate(f.cont, a, b)$value))*(b-a)

cat("Estimate using control variates is", estimate_cont_weibull)
## Estimate using control variates is 0.2014817
var.cont.estimate <- var(g.cont(x) + c_star_weibull * (f.cont(x) - (1/(b-a)) *integrate(f.cont, a, b)$value))
var.cont.estimate
## [1] 1.573838e-06

d) At the end, obtain % variance reduction in each case, and interpret which estimator is more efficient, why?

var.reduction.antithetic = 100 * ((var_classical - var.ant.estimate ) / var_classical)
cat("The control variates approach achived", round(var.reduction.antithetic,3), "%", "reduction in variance.")
## The control variates approach achived 99.896 % reduction in variance.
var.reduction.control = 100 * ((var_classical - var.cont.estimate ) / var_classical)
cat("The antithetic variable approach achived", round(var.reduction.control,3), "%", "reduction in variance.")
## The antithetic variable approach achived 99.081 % reduction in variance.

Q5)

Write an R function which estimates an integral for any given function(f(x)). Your function has to have two more options which are

  • “var.reduc” which takes a boolean (True or False).
  • “type” which takes a string from user as “Antithetic” or “Control”.

If user specifies “var.reduc” = FALSE, your function has to estimate the integral for that given function with classical monte carlo integration method only, then returns the estimated integral value and its variance. However, if user specifies “var.reduc” = TRUE, your function again has to calculate monte carlo integration again, but this time it also has to run a variance reduction algorithm specified in the “type” object. User should define this type object according to which variance reduction technique user want to apply.

THEN, IT RETURNS THE VALUES FOR CLASSICAL MONTE CARLO INTEGRATION AND THE ESTIMATION FOR VARIANCE REDUCTION ALGORITHM (BASED ON THE SPECIFIED “TYPE”). ALSO, IT HAS TO RETURN THE VARIANCES OF THOSE TWO (MC INTEGRAL & SPECIFIED VAR.REDUC METHOD).

Of course you have to consider the case that the user wants to use Control Variates method, he/she has to use another correlated function to find \(c*\) and estimate the result for the integral, so please make sure that your function can also take another function for that purpose. In control variates case, if correlation between f(x) and g(x) is smaller than 0.5, you should give warning as “correlation smaller than 0.5. You should try another f.cont function!!!”. If correlation between f(x) and g(x) is bigger than 0.5, you should print the correlation between them. You should also ask the user if they want to print plot of the fucntion or not. Optionally, your function should be able to print the graph.

(Hint: minimum range, maximum range, graph, var.reduc, type, f, and g should be user defined.)

When your function is ready, please try it with any function you want and check if it is working properly.

a<- function(f,n,low,up,graph=F,var.reduc=F,type, f.cont=1){
 set.seed(1234)
  start1 <- proc.time()

  x<-runif(n,low,up)
  
  Estimate<-mean(sapply(x,f))*(up-low)
  
  Theoritical<-integrate(f,low,up)$value
  
  Error<-abs(Estimate-Theoritical)
  
  var.estimate <-mean(sapply(x,f)^2)*(up-low) - (mean(sapply(x,f))*(up-low))^2
  run.time <- proc.time() - start1

 outcome<-round(rbind(Estimate,Theoritical,Error),5)
    
  
  if(graph){

y <- seq(low,up,0.001)
y.low <- rep(0,times = length(y))

plot(y, fun(y), type = "n",
main = "f(x)",
lwd = 2.5)
lines(y,fun(y.low), col = 'grey')
lines(y,fun(y), col = 'grey')
polygon(c(y, rev(y)), c(fun(y), rev(fun(y.low))),
col = "grey30", border = NA)}

 
if(var.reduc){
  
  if(type=="Antithetic") {
 start2 <- proc.time()
 
x2 <- runif(n/2,low,up)

theta1.1 <- mean(sapply(x2,f)) * (up-low)
theta1.2 <- mean(sapply(up-x2,f)) * (up-low)

exp.ant.estimate1 <- (theta1.1 + theta1.2) / 2
Error.ant<-abs(exp.ant.estimate1-Theoritical)

z1.1 <- f(x2)
z1.2 <- f(up-x2)

var.ant.estimate1 <- (var(z1.1)+var(z1.2)+2*cov(z1.1,z1.2)) / 4

run.time.ant <- proc.time() - start2  
ant.outcome<-matrix(c(Estimate,exp.ant.estimate1,
var.estimate, var.ant.estimate1),nrow=2,dimnames = list(c("classical approach","Antithetic"),c("estimated mean","variance")))

print(ant.outcome)
print(matrix(c(Error.ant),nrow=1,dimnames = list(c("Error"))))
print(run.time)
print(run.time.ant)
  
}
    else if (type=="Control") {
start3 <- proc.time()

g.cont<-f
f.cont <-f.cont


correlation<-cor(g.cont(x),f.cont(x))
        if (correlation<0.5) {print("correlation smaller than 0.5. You should try another f.cont function!!!")}
        else {print(cat("Correlation between g.cont and f.con is",
round(correlation,4),""))}

c_star <- -cov(g.cont(x),f.cont(x)) / var(f.cont(x))


expected.fu <- integrate(f.cont,low,up)$value
exp.cont.estimate1 <- mean(g.cont(x) +c_star * (f.cont(x) - expected.fu)) * (up-low)
Error.cont<-abs(exp.cont.estimate1-Theoritical)
var.cont.estimate1 <- var(g.cont(x) + c_star * (f.cont(x) - expected.fu))
var.cont.estimate1

cont.outcome <- matrix(c(Estimate,exp.cont.estimate1,
var.estimate, var.cont.estimate1),nrow=2,dimnames = list(c("classical approach","control variates"),c("estimated mean","variance")))
print(cont.outcome)

print(matrix(c(Error.cont),nrow=1,dimnames = list(c("Error"))))
run.time.cont <- proc.time() - start3
print(run.time)
print(run.time.cont)

  
}}


else {return(outcome)}

}

fun<-function(x)  exp(x) / (1+x^2) 
fun1<- function(x) 1/1+x
a(fun,10^5,0,1,var.reduc = F, graph = T)
